Here's the recommended setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — singleton: reuse one HttpClient/config across the app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — transient: fresh state each time a page is created
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — transient: new instance per navigation
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes?**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient` and shared config. One instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you cache auth tokens or headers in one place. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each page navigation should get a fresh VM so you don't show stale data from a previous visit. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the VMs — a new page instance per navigation avoids leftover UI state. |

**When would you use Scoped?** In MAUI there's no built-in scope per navigation (unlike ASP.NET's per-request scope), so `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`. Stick with Singleton or Transient unless you manually create scopes.

**Tip:** If `DetailViewModel` needs a parameter (e.g., an item ID), pass it via a navigation query attribute rather than constructor injection:

```csharp
[QueryProperty(nameof(ItemId), "itemId")]
public partial class DetailViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty] private string itemId;
}
```
